{
  "comment_text": {
    "sn2.17:1.1": "Probably not the same individual as the “independent divinity” Subrahmā (<a href='https://suttacentral.net/sn6.6/en/sujato'>SN 6.6</a>–8 and <a href='https://suttacentral.net/dn20/en/sujato#20.1'>DN 20:20.1</a>). In the Rig Veda, <i lang='pi' translate='no'>subrahma</i> meant “good sacred formulation” (Rig Veda 7.16.2, 10.47.3, 10.62.4) ",
    "sn2.17:3.1": "PTS reads <i lang='pi' translate='no'>bojjhaṅgatapasā</i>; Yogācārabhūmi Śarīrārthagāthā 5.2 has<i lang='pi' translate='no'>jñānatapaso</i>; SA 596 seems to pass over <i lang='pi' translate='no'>bojjha</i>; while SA2 181 has <span lang='lzh'>智慧者</span>, “wise one”. I follow Bodhi in accepting the MS reading, <i lang='pi' translate='no'>nāññatra bojjhā tapasā</i>. ",
    "sn2.17:4.1": "This prose fragment is unusual here. Such endings are normally abbreviated in the Pali, although they are retained in the Chinese. "
  },
